The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Uplink rules

 New Delhi, Dec. 6: The new uplinking rules are now in place, reports our special correspondent.

 The information and broadcasting ministry has notified television uplinking guidelines that put a slab of 26 per cent on foreign equity in the company seeking permission to uplink.

 It also gives full access to Prasar Bharati to procure feed for all cricket matches featuring India in India and the semi-finals and finals of international competitions.

 The new rules have become operational from December 2. It will supersede guidelines for uplinking from India that have been announced since July 2000. This includes guidelines for uplinking of news and current affairs channels from India in March 2003, which was amended in August 2003.

 The uplinking will be granted with conditions. Sports channels or sports rights management companies having TV broadcasting rights will be given permission on condition that they share feed with Prasar Bharati for national and international sporting events.

 Prasar Bharati will be given the feed for terrestrial transmission and DTH broadcasting of the events of national importance, held in India or abroad.

 The events of national importance will be determined by the ministry of information and broadcasting in consultation with ministry of sports and youth affairs, the guidelines said. In case of cricket, these shall include all matches featuring India and the semi-finals and finals of international competitions.

 The company seeking uplinking should have a net worth of Rs 1.5 crore for single TV channel and Rs 1 crore for each additional one. Permission will be granted for 10 years.

 It will be obligatory for the company to comply with programme and advertising codes in the Cable Television Networks (Regulation) Act, 1995.




